@amr-eniou-3r This issue is from March 2020 ... sounds like enough time.
Don't get me wrong, 
I appreciate all the work and use Flutter because I love it and I trust the devs.

I would encourage everyone participating in this discussion to consider our code of conduct, which requires that all discussions be actively welcoming and friendly. That includes conversations about contributions by other contributors (including Google employees). If one day you are feeling entitled, I encourage you to take the day off commenting on open source projects.

That said, we agree that hot reload is valuable.

@michaellee8 I'm not directly familiar with this work but I'll pass it on to the Dart team, thanks.

@michaellee8 - what I demoed in the past with WebPack is already wired up in Flutter.

It's what we call "hot restart" (a stateless hot reload).  Technically, it's stateless on the Dart side (which we can reset automatically) but semi-stateful on the DOM side (which we cannot).  Depending on your app, it can look more or less stateful.  

To this this robustly and efficiently (similar to native support), we'd need a fairly thorough restructuring of the Dart -> JS compiler (dartdevc).  ( @sigmundch )

@Levi-Lesches - good questions.  We're still trying to assess.  Some of the approaches we've discussed would de-optimize the generated code, which might result in more (too much?) sluggishness during debugging.

@michaellee8 - that wouldn't provide "normal" Flutter/Dart hot reload (the Dart VM walks objects in the heap, not just component state vars).  Not sure how well that would work in practice, but I *think* this would be a breaking change in Flutter to explicitly track what to save/restore.

@jlubeck (and others) - thanks.  It's useful to under when Desktop is and isn't good for development in practice.
